description.text:
The RaceBox Mini is a 3D printed die-cast car carrier with a twist. Open the lid, remove the cars, lock the handle in place, and flip it over to make a ramp for jumping and racing!

My three-year-old son provided the inspiration for the RaceBox. He loves his!

There are two versions of the RaceBox: full and mini. This is the RaceBox Mini, which holds two cars. The full holds four. The STL and STEP files for the full version are available on Etsy here.

The full version has an Easter egg function. If you can find it, I'll be stoked.

The RaceBox Mini is 89x198x45mm.
The RaceBox (4 cars) is 169x198x45mm.

It's easy!

Just pop those parts off your printer, snap the handle into place, and go race some cars!!

By many many iterations.

The RaceBox has a lot of important fits, and I needed it to be completely usable by my two year old. That meant I had to carefully dial in all of the springs and clips to make them strong enough to hold together, but malleable enough for him to open the box.

Additionally, I just kept trying to make it better... The full version saw ten printed iterations!!

The RaceBox Mini and Full version were designed in Autodesk Fusion 360.

The RaceBox was designed 'in half' like this. Then I mirrored the half to make a whole. Pro tip. I designed a really nifty snap for the handle, to keep it from coming out. I later found out that removing the handle enables a really cool feature on the full version... It's an Easter egg function! So this beautiful snap no longer exists.
printing a color picture!

I like cardstock miniatures for gaming, like SJ Games's Cardboard Heroes (http://www.warehouse23.com/products/cardboard-heroes-fantasy-set-01-player-characters). They're inexpensive, easy to carry and store, and save me the trouble of painting. But with their light weight and small bases, they've got stability issues. These plastic bases, inspired by the ones for the Dungeon Fantasy Roleplaying Game Kickstarter, are designed to fix that problem. Instead of folding up a stand-up triangle, just pop the cardboard miniature into the base. Much more stable, and since it's folded flat, more resistant to crushing. They're sized for one-inch-per-hex hex maps, and include one-hex (for people) as well as two-hex and three-hex versions for larger creatures.

Scoreboard

Wooden box

There is no board game without some kind of a box and thus I thought to redesign mine and lasercut it to enhance the handmade quality of the replacement set! The logo is designed from scratch and has been engraved on the wooden surface. Also, a hole on the right side of the lid makes opening the box easy!

In need of a crankcase ventilation catch can for my diesel powered vehicle, I was surprised at the cost of commercial ones, and the fact that they used a filter that had to be replaced. I also noticed that the other catch cans on Thingiverse don't utilize much internal surface area to catch the oil droplets as much as possible. So I created this device in Cubify Invent to print on a 3D printer. This uses an internal baffle network made from the plastic in lieu of a filter. Since there is so much surface area inside this catch can for oil droplets to condense, and since it's made from plastic (I used ABS), there should be no need for a replaceable filter element.
The nipple closest to the can opening is the inlet, and the one below that is the outlet. Plumb the inlet from the crankcase vent line, and the outlet to the air box. Enjoy a clean, non-oil soaked intake tract. The small nipple on the bottom of the can should be connected to a small hose and capped off; this is the oil collection and drain hose. Check it every now and then and drain off oil as needed.
NOTE:
This is a LONG print! We're talking 5-7 days for a regular FDM printer! All of those small internal vertical baffle elements really will tax your printer. Are they needed? Probably. The more there are, the more oil will be separated from the crankcase blow-by gases.
The cap surface is set up to use a 124mm x 3.5mm O-ring. It might seal well enough without it.

description.text:
Edit - 1/24/2018 - I removed the drag chain links as I've greatly refined the design. The refined links, along with other components will be joined together in a separate collection and I will add a link to that in this description. I've also went ahead and changed out the Super X Motor Block with the updated chain link connectors.

Drag Chain Collection - https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2769475

Edit - Happy New Years!!! - 1/1/2018 - Super X Duct (rev 6). This time I added a BLTouch mount on one of the downspouts and increased the duct openings by another 0.5mm and also increased the downward pitch of the jets as well as the manifold(5º). So between the downward pitch of the jets as well as the increased pitch of the manifold, there's plenty of clearance to blow air only at the print and not on the hot end.

Edit - 12/27/2017 - Yet another duct revision (Rev 5). This time I rotated the legs backwards 2º that will in turn force the skirt to rotate forward by that much when mounted which will translate better aim of the air jets towards the print and less on the hot end.

Edit - 12/26/2017 - I altered the drag chain link connectors to include a tapered inlet to assist in chain connection and removal.

Edit - 12/4/2017 - I refined my drag links by giving the receiving side a slightly wider stance and a bevel on the opening to improve joining and disjoining of links. I also added a custom bridge support that is very easily removed with a needle nose pliers. Just crush both sides of the support and twist and it cleanly pops right out, but if you're more comfortable with your slicer's support structures, there are also STLs with no custom support. I will soon be designing a bed and frame mount to confine the heated bed cables. For best results, print them slow @25mm/s, 0.2 first layer and 0.2 layer height. Once complete, I will be back to finish my control boxes.

Edit - 11/27/2017 Thanks to Jim Brown for giving me the measurements for a single extruder heat sink mount, I grafted this in for those with single nozzle kits.

Edit - 11/22/2017 I added 2 more revisions to the ducts. Rev 3 gets very close to the bed, but I use bulldog clips to hold my glass and Rev 3 kept getting caught up. Rev 4 backs it off just another mm and clears the bulldog clips. I aimed the air jets down just a tad more on both.

Missing parts (Mechanism & Turnwheel) can be found @ this link as my design began as a remix of that Thing.
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1730521

As of about 10/15/2017, I've been using my own remix of this project which entailed remixing my other designs, so rather than update all of my other remixes, I just put everything I have here. What I did different was to bring the BLTouch outside the carriage and away from the heat block, made the carriage a 3 wheel car, greatly updated the fan ducts that print great and blow as desired. I still want to do some added tests, but I've already printed some stuff and everything came out good. I also added in receivers to run chain links of either side above the belt. I also made very nice drag chain links to hide wires, no hardware needed and absolutely no feeding wires through the links, just a slalom around the keepers which makes the links an open link design. I am also thinking of altering the new ring duct so I can mount the BLTouch from the leg mount screws as the probe can now contact the Z rails which I don't want. My overall intent to have the X car travel as far as possible to ensure each of the nozzles can cover 100% of the bed rather than left nozzle covering from 0-190 and left 10-200 leaving only 10-190 that both nozzles can reach.

Up next, a case to hold a Raspberry Pi 3B, MKS Base v1.4, 2 channel Sainsmart Relay Module and the LCD into one unit. I really want to relocate the electronics before putting an enclosure around the printer.

description.text:
Work in Progress, print at your own risk.

The design is printable with a Stereolithography (SLA) printer only. A resin or powder based one like the Form 1+ https://formlabs.com/store/us/form-1/

I started a bit of a project designing and building a retro Pi TLR camera. So far I have a the shell, lens assemblies, internal mirror for the viewing lens and body designed.

How it works:
The taking lens projects onto a 36mm ground glass square. A 8MP pi camera with a wide angle lens will then snap a picture of the projected image on the ground glass. The ground glass should produce a film grain effect that will be a physical part of the camera. The design will likely to be redesigned throughout the build. I also designed a electronics bay that will easily screw onto the back.

The camera is also quite small in size to be more portable.

Use:
Just like real TLR camera's you hold the camera at waist level and look down at the 36mm ground glass. Using the focus knob to bring the subject into focus and take a picture with the 12mm button in the front. Their is no "live" picture on a LCD or electronic display but rather a pure optical viewfinder. You will only be able to see the picture when you transfer them later or over WiFi though the Pi.

This is designed as a riser for linkages on the MaslowCNC, specifically the one made and sold by pillageTHENburn. This standoff has a recess in the top that allows the included washer and locknut to sit inside the riser. Enough room was also allowed for a Kobalt brand socket. After securing the spacer down to the sled a second larger washer should ride on top of the riser, followed by the linkage, then another washer and another lock nut.

10/24/17 Update. Everything seems to bolt up well. The 10-24 bolts thread onto the standoffs. I ran the same drill big I used to drill holes in my sled down the standoffs so I wouldn't have to thread them on. The 10-24 pan head bolts that came with the linkage were just a little too short for me to screw the nut on. I've ordered 4.5" long screws which I think will work well.

10/27/17 Update. The chains are parallel to the work surface without the sled on any wood to be cut. I've now uploaded version 2 (v2) that shortens the standoffs so the chains will be parallel when on 3/4" plywood. Should also work fine on 1/2" plywood too. I recommend version 2.

description.text:
The best advice I've found regarding bed adhesion, is to use a 1:10 solution of white glue (PVA) in water, spread onto a glass printbed with a brush, and let it dry using the heated bed. However, there were a few issues with this:

  • This works extremely well with PLA, it becomes so adhered that if a part has a solid bottom, it can take 10s of kg to separate if the glass is still hot
  • As the glass cools and shrinks, the part pops off the glass on its own, however, if still on the printer, this takes several minutes (the metal core of the printbed stores a lot of heat)
  • Normally you add more PVA solution before each print, but after ~15 cycles, dirt and oils accumulate and the glass needs to be washed. PVA is easily removed with warm water, but the glass needs to dry afterwards (you can use isopropyl alcohol to speed this part up, though)
  • Finally, in a commercial printing setting, it's important not to waste time between prints

Therefore, I designed this simple cooling rack. By having two identical glass panes, I can swap them after a print is finished, with zero downtime. The open back of the rack allows the glass to cool down fast, large prints pop off on their own in few minutes.

Friction from the cardboard is usually enough to hold the box closed, but a dab of Uhu or white glue will solve it if not.

description.text:
I really like this action cam from JVC, especially its timelapse mode for recording prints. However my battery is old and holds little charge, and most prints last longer than the batt.

Therefore, I made a dummy battery to emulate a fully charged one! This will lead two cables out the back of your camera that you can then connect to a power supply. I use a DC-DC converter that you can get from your favorite online retailer for cheap. Just make sure you have a constant 3.7 - 3.8v

The design works best with stranded wire and low layer heights, because of the "nubs" intended for securing the wire. If, like me, you simply cannot get that to work, grab some solid wire and a small drill bit.

The grooves will snugly accommodate 1.2mm external dia. wire, experiment with thicknesses around 22AWG

It probably bears highlighting that you lose the water resistant feature of your camera while using this mod.

description.text:
I use a glass test tube for ABS juice (acetone/ABS) that I use to help prints stick, but the test tube rack is way over there [points across room], and that's a bit inconvenient. So I made a little holder for it that snaps the ~16mm diameter test tube into place right onto the frame of the Prusa Mendel -- or any other 5/16 inch or 8mm rod. 
The clip alone can hold the test tube in place, but I didn't want the tube to vibrate out on long prints, so there's a base that keeps it in place. 
If anyone is interested, I can clean up the code in a bit and get it online, too. It's parametric, so you can change a bunch of the properties to fit other sized equipment.

3) Insert test tube.

description.text:
https://www.instructables.com/id/3D-Printed-HeadLamp-With-Constant-Current-Circuit-/

For more info on how to do it, please visit the above link.

Lights are one of the most essential items that any backpacker would consider in his checklist. Among all the light sources which a backpacker chooses, headlamps are the best. This is because, a typical headlamp has its own advantages and practical applications. One can always argue that it can easily be replaced by a handheld flashlight or torch. But our own safety is the number one priority that matters while living outdoors. During certain situations when our survival matters the most, our hands may not be free all the time to hold a flash light. So it is always better to be hands free.

Moreover, these headlamps can be strapped anywhere. Also, one can always keep the headlamps in their hands anytime if it makes them feel better. Hence it can be used for camping, hiking, biking and various other creative applications. Overall, Headlamps are a must for anyone who wishes to have a safe night hiking experience.

In this Instructable, you'll be able to learn how I made my own 3D printed Headlamp and the circuit that I used to make the Headlamp reliable and long lasting. You might wonder what is the need for doing this project when there are so many cheap headlamps available in the market. Please beware of such cheap products. Most of those products don't contain constant current sources to drive the LEDs. They may stop functioning any time. Hence they are not that reliable. There are some products in the market that contain constant current circuits too. But they are too costly.

So to cherish the joy of making and learning how a professional headlamp circuit works, this is the right place.

The main features of my headlamp are 36hrs of battery back up under Low power mode and 10hrs of battery backup in High power mode. It can be attached to any head ie it is that flexible to use.

The switch is located on top the power plug and is therefore easily accessible, and the power plug is rigidly mounted to the frame with the 220V wires pretty well protected... what else ?

My kitchen has 3 power outlets that are shared by multiple appliance and it is a chore to identify which cables is for which appliance.

I designed this set of tags to quickly and easily identify the cables. They are very quick to print and I find them very useful. Hope you find it useful for yourself as well!

Notes:

I used a large layer height (0.32mm) as the printing this tag is a retraction nightmare, especially for complicated icons. Large layer height can help to mitigate the flow rate of the filament which hopefully results in lesser artifacts in the print. Plus they help to speed up the print!

I also set the horizontal expansion option in Cura to -0.2mm in order to force the slicing to make a single layer thick wall. You may want to play around with that setting to get something that works for you.

  • For the Nespresso icon, note that the right side of the N also won't come out as it would be air printing. You may try to hack the print setting by turning off retraction completely and hope that the air printed part can print on the stringing itself, but I didn't try that.

My goal was to design an easy to print padlock with an unibody housing, as simple as possible and working.

description.text:
The Sony DSC-QX10 is a "lens style" camera with a 10x optical zoom. It's great for filming and for taking fotos, and can be controlled from your smartphone. The camera is available as used on e-bay for prices around 70-80$/€.

This project contains the parts to build an inexpensive 2D gimbal for it, attachable to a selfie stick (mine is a Foneso). I've also created a quadrocopter gimbal with these parts, but am facing vibration issues there, and will only publish that after having resolved the vibrations. The battery box is from this project. The smartphone holder is from this one.

See a short demo clip of the camera on the gimbal here: https://youtu.be/cAwWw3J0k2o

The parts for building a 2D gimbal stick are:

  • ActionArm8Bit.stl - the arm between the selfie stick and the tilt motor
  • ArmToRoll.stl - the arm between the tilt and the roll motors
  • QX10-CamPlate.stl - the plate holding the camera and the IMU

You need these other parts:

  • a 2D 8bit Brushless Gimbal Controller and an IMU. The IMU used here has a size of 21x13 mm. - Search ebay for e.g. "BGC 3.0" - ~10$/€
  • a ferrite ring - wind the I2C cable for the IMU 4 times through this ring to avoid I2C errors and gimbal lock-ups/ mis-behaviors
  • two 2804 hollow shaft motors with screws - search e-bay for "2804 hollow shaft" - each ~10$/€

Alternatively, buy a complete 2D gimbal kit including these parts, screws, cables, etc. by searching e-bay for e.g. "2axis gimbal" - ~40$/€

To use a different controller/ IMU or different motors, have a look at the OpenSCAD source files in the zip! They already contain definitions for some other boards and motors, and you can change them by editing one or a few lines in the code (docs not yet available...). To build the parts, you need OpenSCAD 2016 or newer.

  4. i used a part of 2mm(or mb 1.5mm, not sure) drill as an axis. Actually anything that fits the size can be used
  5. finally just solder wires to the buttons and pass them where required
  6. optionally a piece of different color plastic can be glued in the middle of 'lever' for even better look - see pics

It is designed to be as compact as possible to stick to the original dimensions. Because of this the z endstop is not mounted directly to the carriage. You might use a end stop switch or see below for a solution with a proximity sensor.

  • NEMA 17 Pancake Motor (20mm thick body, not 26mm)
  • 50x15 Radial Fan
  • M3 Nuts: 7x Standard or Nyloc

A compact base for the Tarot T-2D Gimbal to moint it to a TC-R 220 or a QAV-R.

There is no place to mount the controller yet, so you have to find a way how to mount yours.
I screwed a small plate to the top plate to which I zip tied the board. Afterwards I put on this nice cover https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:619014 from Holger Stilke (ILse51 )to protect it.

Hardware required:

  • 4 x rubber dampers (I use the stock ones, on the softer side)
  • 2 x m2.5 x 8 screws (stock) & washers
  • 2 x m2 x 10 screws
  • 2 x m2 x nuts & washers

Mounting holes:

  • front holes 35mm apart
  • rear holes 31.5mm apart
  • rear holes 42mm behind the front holes

Printer:

Anet A8

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

0.2 mm

Infill:

100 %

Notes:

You can use basically any material you wan't to. I printed with PLA.

Assembly

Compare to the last picture, to see if you mounted everything correctly.

1) Mount the rubber dampers to the top plate, then "connect" the top and middle plate by mounting the middle plate to the other end of the dampers.

2) Screw the gimbal with the stock (or other) m 2.5 screws to the mid plate, use some washers between screw head and the plate.
Keep in mind: the chamfered side of the upper plate is the back side.

3) Drill out the holes on the two posts of the base with a 2mm drill (if required) and insert a m2 nut in each of the slots (back side also chamfered)

4) Take the gimbal assembly (consisting of the gimbal with upper and lower plate) and place it onto the base, insert a m2x10 screw in the holes aligning with the ones of the base. Tighten the screws, they should reach down into the nuts.

Tip: You might have to stop the nuts from spinning with a screwdriver whilst you screw in the screw.

Mounting off the controllboard

This is how I mounted the board:

1) Cut out a plate, roughly the size of the board.

2) Drill a 2mm hole into the center.

3) Unscrew the rear screw that hold the upper plate to the base, put it through the plate you just cut out and screw it back in with. The plate should not touch the metal post of the gimbal (comp. to the picture).

4) Zip-tie, screw or stick (doublesided tape) the gimbal controller to your plate.

be careful that the m2 screw in the middle of the plate doesn't short out the controller!

5) If you want print out this nice cover: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:619014 , you might have to shave cover out on some places if you e.g. zip tied the controller to the plate, so that it can sit securely.

I had to shave out a bit of the upper front edge of the cover so that it wouldn't touch the gimbel.

title: Tronxy X5s e3d v6 Mount With Belt Aligner
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
e3d v6 mount for the Tronxy X5s.

Please note I made a mistake buying the idlers I have as they are made for 9mm belts, hence why they don't actually look aligned in my pictures. They do align though using the stock bearing sandwich, or proper GT2 idler pulleys.

Features;

  • Mounts at 4 places for stability and stength (original hotend m3 holes, and the 2 top wheel holes)
  • Aligns the 2 angled belts, which is very important for stress relief and accuracy.
  • Integrated X end-stop mounting

Please note, if you have already snipped your belts, they probably won't be long enough to use the belt aligner part, since they need to be about 40mm longer to wrap around the aligners. However, if you haven't already, you should definitely consider getting some proper GT2 fiber reinforced belts.

Print all parts as already oriented with no supports. You will need 2x 'tronxy x5s bellt aligner wheel'

You will need;

2x M3x6mm bolts (for bottom mounting)
2x M4x30 bolts (for belt aligner mounting)
2x M4 nuts (preferably nyloc) (for belt aligner mounting)
2x M3 nuts (preferably nyloc) (for e3d v6 mounting)
2x M3x30 bolts (for e3d v6 mounting)

Installation;

'MAIN PART' refers to the stl file 'tronxy x5s e3d v6 mtg + belt aligner''
'CAP' refers to the stl file 'tronxy x5s e3d v6 mtg cap'
'ALIGNER' refers to the stl file 'tronxy x5s bellt aligner wheel'

1) Remove everything from the carriage (except belts), and take the x end stop off the acrylic plate (but keep the screws)

2) If your belts have at least another 50mm after the ziptie, just trim the ziptie off the BOTTOM LEFT and TOP RIGHT belt. Otherwise you would need to install some new belts, in which case do not put zipties on the BOTTOM LEFT and TOP RIGHT belts.

3) remove the 2 M3 hex spacers

4) Remove the top 2 wheels

5) Insert the M3 nuts into the back of the MAIN PART, make sure they are pushed all the way down and level

6) Hold the MAIN PART in place on the carriage, put the M5 wheel bolts back through and screw in place on the gantry

7) screw the M3x6mm bolts in at the bottom

8) Insert E3d-v6, push the M3x30 bolts through the CAP, and bolt onto the MAIN PART

9) Push the ALIGNERS in place, so that the BOTTOM LEFT and TOP RIGHT belts wrap around them

10) Push the M4x30 bolts up through the bottom of the MAIN PART, through the ALIGNERS and out the top, screw the M4 nuts on top and tighten them up nicely.

10) Pull the belts tight and finish them off with a zip tie. (You should do with your steppers mounted as forward as possible, so you can tension the belts after)

11) Screw x endstop in the provided holes with the original screws

For my mega gantry brackets see: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2594291
For my micro cooling fan duct see: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2469775

WARNING: ALWAYS OPERATE THE CENTRIFUGE WITH THE COVER CLOSED.

This is version 2.0 of our previous F.Lab DIYbio centrifuge: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1175393

Video demonstration is here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rTMLX00tXjc

Features:

  1. Incorporates 12V DC motor;
  2. microswitch for auto-cutoff when cover is open;
  3. high-res (400 sides) rotor based on: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2479765;
  4. rocker switch;
  5. extra space for Arduino Nano and;
  6. 2 cover options: solid 3D printed & for acrylic window (version pictured above).

Description

It uses a 12V DC motor and a simple rocker switch. It also has provisions for adding in a microswitch and enough room for adding in a micocontroller (like an Arduino Nano) to add timing and cycle functions.

There is also 2 versions of the cover. One is a solid 3D printed cover. The other is printed in 2 sections and friction welded or glued together with a piece of acrylic in between to create a window (pictured).

The original SketchUp file (.skp) is included.

The rotor has been improved greatly from the low-poly original rotor thanks to the OpenSCAD model published by Thomas Kircher. His code has been slightly modified from around 200 sides to 400 sides and the dimensions slightly modified to be more even. The OpenSCAD code (.scad) is also included.

The spindle connector for the rotor is provisional. We're working on something better that will leave the rotor balanced perfectly. For now, it uses a sawed off 5mm diameter bolt and a nut glued into the spindle connector.

This is still in progress. Come back for the rest of the files, photos and video for the working centrifuge and links to build tutorials.

description.text:
Enclosure for a super accurate Arduino GPS clock. Basic description and sketch here:
learn.adafruit.com/arduino-clock/software?view=all
I expanded this with a charger, Lipo, on/off switch and a touch toggle switch.

The display is bright enough to be visible through the printed enclosure so have fun with different colors for the outer shell. Sand the contact areas on the inner part so that the shell slips smoothly over it. I printed this in PETG for dimensional accuracy but PLA should be fine. Shell prints without support, ad a brim for adhesion.

Power on/off is wired to GND and EN on the powerboost board.
Toggle switch powers the Metro mini and display together. Just powering on/off the display doesn't work but both together come on immediately anyway. GPS is powered as long as the Power boost charger is on.
Added the Lipo to be able to carry this around as GPS signal inside the house may be difficult to find at any given time. The display seems to draw a fair amount of current so the lipo lasts about 36 to 48 hours on a full charge. Had an antenna cable around, but this seems not to be necessary.

This is a little piece of plastic I designed to replace a broken latch on the spacebar of my Model M keyboard. Since nobody seem to sell any spare parts for Model Ms on eBay, I had to fix my broken one.
As of now it's only designed to replace the latch on the right side of the key, since it's big enough to not to fit into the tight space on the left side, where it's obstructed by the unused key stem housing.

Clean all surfaces, leftovers of a skirt (if there was any) with a file or a piece of sandpaper. Depending on your printer calibration, the stabilizer bar hole might require a touch too.

Also, it really helps if there's a part of original latch left on a key, as it lets you to precisely align where to glue the replacement piece.
I drew the latch contour in LibreCAD and extruded it with OpenSCAD oneliner. There's not much to it at all, really.

How it works:

  1. According to the time provided by RTC, Arduino moves the 28BYJ-48 stepping motor.
  2. The right drum moves one step per minute, and the left drum moves one step per hour. Attach 60 plates to each drum.
  3. With a photo reflector in the drum, Arduino knows the absolute angle.

For the four digit split flap display clock I made previously, improved the following things:

  1. Reduced the number of motors from 4 to 2.
  2. Remove of gear by coaxial arrangement of drum and motor.
  3. Wiring hidden in the frame.
  4. Reduces the influence of ambient light by changing the position of the infrared sensor.

It takes a long time to paste the number seal. It took me a day. If you have a printer with a dual nozzle and you can make 3D data of a plate with numbers, you can easily print it.
